    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-06-25T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-06-25T02:00:00-05:00" n="501"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d501">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.115 Hunt Company, William/35: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hankow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-06-25T15:00:00+08:00"
                            >June 25, 1938—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received June 25—10:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>316. Shanghai’s 874, June 20, 8 p.m.<note n="81" xml:id="d501fn81">Not
                        printed.</note> Admiral LeBreton<note n="82" xml:id="d501fn82">Rear Adm.
                        David McDougal LeBreton, commander, United States Yangtze Patrol.</note>
                    informs me of receipt of letter from captain of <hi rend="italic">Monocacy</hi>
                    at Kiukiang stating that he has received word from China Merchants<note n="83"
                        xml:id="d501fn83">China Merchants’ Steam Navigation Company.</note> at that
                    place that it will give him list of China Merchants floating equipment there
                    which will be prepared to accompany <hi rend="italic">Monocacy</hi> if and when
                        <hi rend="italic">Monocacy</hi> proceeds up river. China Merchants equipment
                    to be filled with Chinese refugees. I have asked LeBreton to inform <hi
                        rend="italic">Monocacy</hi> that American Government does not recognize
                    right of China Merchants property to American protection and that he should so
                    inform China Merchants at Kiukiang. But situation is fraught with danger for <hi
                        rend="italic">Monocacy</hi> should these China steamers decide to surround
                    and follow <hi rend="italic">Monocacy</hi> upstream in view of Japanese practice
                    of bombing merchant shipping on river. Shanghai should without delay tell Hunt
                    and Company to advise China Merchants to leave Kiukiang independently of <hi
                        rend="italic">Monocacy</hi>. I have suggested to Admiral that <hi
                        rend="italic">Monocacy</hi> should inform Japanese through Shanghai of its
                    whereabouts and whether merchant shipping nearby.</p>
                <p>Sent to Shanghai.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
